  "texts": [
    "These processes could include, for example, the development of guidelines on whether red-teaming is most effective when conducted internally or externally and when it should be conducted (i.e., before and/or after public release of the model and whether red-teaming activities should be ongoing while the model is publicly available).Evaluation team composition introduces biases.",
    "The goal of team member selection seems to be ensuring variety in the risk areas explored during red-teaming.",
    "One way to do so is by handpicking experts with different backgrounds, as noted by prior work on interdisciplinary collaboration within AI teams [102,46]; another is by randomly sampling the population through crowdsourcing.",
    "Both have drawbacks: there may be bias in expert selection [70,36], and crowdworkers have limited resources in terms of time, compute, and relevant expertise [155].",
    "It is difficult to say what the ideal balance between expert and non-technical stakeholders would be, but prior crowdsourcing research suggests a hybrid approach could help address some of the pitfalls associated with each type of team composition [74,158,36]."
  ],
